		<title>Raise your cellphones in support of the South African Police Service! [OPINION]</title>
		<link>http://54beats.com/Main/?p=303</link>
		<comments>http://54beats.com/Main/?p=303#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 08 Dec 2008 21:55:16 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Duane</dc:creator>
		
		<category><![CDATA[Current Affairs]]></category>

		<category><![CDATA[Personal]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://54beats.com/Main/?p=303</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[DuaneRecently, in his blog Constitutionally Speaking, Pierre de Vos, the eminent Constitutional law expert, mentioned that the ANC has proposed that a “revamped Independent Complaints Directorate (ICD) deal initially with all criminal complaints against the police”. As de Vos points out, the move is disturbing for a number of reasons. It is unconstitutional because it [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[Duane<p>Recently, in his blog Constitutionally Speaking, Pierre de Vos, the eminent Constitutional law expert, mentioned that the ANC has proposed that a “revamped Independent Complaints Directorate (ICD) deal initially with all criminal complaints against the police”. As de Vos points out, the move is disturbing for a number of reasons. It is unconstitutional because it in essence makes the police exempt from The Rule of Law, a founding value of the new democratic dispensation, where everyone is held accountable to the justice system regardless of their social position. It infringes on the right of the National Prosecuting Authorities’ right to execute their Constitutionally protected mandate to institute criminal proceedings without “fear, favour or prejudice”. Most significantly, it sends a message to the police that they would not be held accountable for the increasingly heavy handed and sometimes blatantly illegal manner in which they execute their duties, especially in situations of face-to-face, hands-on engagement with suspects.</p>
<p><span id="more-303"></span></p>
<p>The proposal comes as no surprise though since in many ways it is merely a cherry on an already iced cake. For one, it should be noted that de Vos perhaps over-estimates the ICD’s powers. I am not a law expert or anything, but it is common knowledge that the ICD is a body that investigates complaints made against the police, the findings of which are forwarded to the relevant authorities in the form of their recommendations. Those in authority, in other words other higher ranking police officers, then consult the recommendations and decide on a course of action. It is well known that police services are galvanised by a powerful sense of loyalty towards their fellow brothers and sisters, and, as such, when given the opportunity, they will ardently defend the public reputation of those in their ranks accused of some injustice. So, in that case, what do you think happens in the majority of cases where the ICD recommends that the police were at fault and that a serious course of action be taken—the officer in question is relieved of his gun and badge and sent to the cells?</p>
<p>Secondly, as we may recall, some months ago the Justice Minister (if I’m not mistaken), tacitly granted the police force 007 status when she pronounced that they go ahead and “shoot to kill” those miscreants who failed to respond to conventional forms of communication. Ironically, her wish came true some weeks after when Gauteng police officers smoked a family of five as they made their escape from a team of masked robbers ransacking their home. Clearly, the new proposal serves to simply ratify the state’s increasing tendency to shirk and even flout its responsibility to uphold the rule of law and its accountability to the people.</p>
<p>Now, it is easy to take a liberal, romantic humanist line on this and throw a tearful, mortifying tantrum about the injustice of it all, and blame it on the arrogance of the ANC government. It isn’t so easy however when your chubby-cheeked, Harry-Potter loving, straight-A’s, UCT-bound, fifteen year old daughter has been jackrolled by a team of HIV infested hardened criminals known to you, and the police tell you that nothing can be done because of some legal technicality. It isn’t so easy when your life-partner’s face is blown away in a hijacking and the police are unable to arrest the suspects out of fear of exchanging fire with them in public. We have to acknowledge that the South African Police Services (SAPS) work under extraordinary circumstances and deal with a special brand of deviant, which means they require powers that transcend those accorded to ordinary citizens. In this way, we should be tolerant and accepting of the accident’s and minor mishaps that occur along the way. A family here, a brutal beating of an innocent civilian there, these are but a few of the concessions we South Africans have to make to maintain the lustre of the Rainbow Nation.</p>
<p>Thus, as patriotic citizens of this beautiful nation we should do everything in our power to support them in their efforts. Here is how I propose we go about it. We start a website tentatively entitled SAPSuncut.co.za which we could use as a platform to express our appreciation for the hard work the police do on our behalf. SAPSuncut would be like a local version of YouTube dedicated exclusively to the valiant efforts of the police service. Here members of the public will be able to upload their privately recorded video clips of police officers executing their duties, or rather, dramatic footage of crime busting in action. On many occasions I’ve passed by a scene where SAPS officers were engaged in hand to hand skirmishes with resistant suspects, often pausing to marvel at how well trained the police were in martial arts and other hand to hand combat styles as they performed elaborate headlocks, submission holds or delivered crippling blows with feet, head and hands. If there was an appropriate forum for uploading such graphic and riveting video footage I would surely have whipped out my cellphone and used it to record the event, wouldn’t you?</p>
<p>We could have a running pole on the homepage of the “Ultimate Bad Asses” showcasing video footage of some of SA’s most frequently captured, and most ruthless coppers, as voted by you the public, massacring fiends of all shapes and sizes. In cases where multiple video’s of the same incident is uploaded we could arrange them so one could view different angles of the unfolding action: a headlock here, a tooth-dislodging punch to one side, a bone-crushing baton over the face on the other.</p>
<p>Lets work on this people, especially now that its summer. Let’s give the cops a big thank you from us. Can you imagine how flattering it would be for them to have a crowd of onlookers pointing their camera phones, recording them in the course of their duties? How happy wouldn’t they be seeing themselves on screen brutalising deviant punks, knowing full well that millions of people across the world planning their trips to SA for the 2010 Soccer World Cup would get some peace of mind that the SA police service is capable of ensuring their safety? I cannot think of a better way of saluting the police. Who’s with me on this?</p>
<p>_______________<br />Click the Author link below to access the Authors site&#8230;<br />
<br />Author&#8217;s Yougler  Profile is at &nbsp;<a href="">Duane</a>.</p>
<p>This post was submitted by Duane.</p>]]></content:encoded>
