		<category><![CDATA[Police Brutality]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://54beats.com/Main/?p=301</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[SabreBy Lyle Petersen

Refer to Police Shielded from the law by Pierre De Vos&#8230;
It seems as if steps are being taken to grant further priviledges to the police, with statements made that police do not have to be subject to the same treatment as ordinary criminals.
The Cape Times reports this morning that the ANC wants to [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[Sabre<p>By Lyle Petersen</p>
<p><img src="http://54beats.com/images/brutal.jpg" alt="Police Brutality" /></p>
<p>Refer to Police Shielded from the law by Pierre De Vos&#8230;</p>
<p>It seems as if steps are being taken to grant further priviledges to the police, with statements made that police do not have to be subject to the same treatment as ordinary criminals.</p>
<p>The Cape Times reports this morning that the ANC wants to protect members of the South African Police Service from being dragged into court “to clear their names” when a criminal complaint is filed against them. According to the report:</p>
<p><span id="more-301"></span></p>
<p><em>[T]he party has proposed that a revamped Independent Complaints Directorate (ICD) deal initially with all criminal complaints against police.</em></p>
<p><em>ANC members, who discussed the issue during a meeting of the conference’s peace and stability commission yesterday, argued that police should not be subjected to the same treatment as “ordinary criminals” when faced with being charged with a crime.</em></p>
<p><em>This amounted to the “criminalisation” of officers simply because they were accused of an offence, one delegate said. A delegate who attended the discussion said the proposal meant, for example, that if an officer “shoots someone who poses a danger to the public, (the ICD) will … determine whether to refer the case for further investigation and prosecution”.</em></p>
<p>This conduct as indicated feeds the idea that they should be exempt from ordinary laws.  The ICD has the potential to shield them from the very laws that protect us. Coupled with lack of proper training in dealing with situations, and a feeling of little importance in society may fuel their need for violence.</p>
<p>Are we reverting back to the days of Apartheid? Should we answer a violent society by allowing more violence to be perpertrated in the hope of salvaging the situation. This &quot;solution&quot; instead of training police or using smarter tactics. This “shoot to kill” attitude in response to threats such as the Xenophobia issue is a drawback to same attitude adopted in response to Apartheid insurgency.</p>
<p>The past year has shown the capabilities of the police. At times they deserve commendment for their efforts. But should they be granted desperate solutions granting excessive power and short term relief in desperate situations. Laws are there to protect society, and preventing certain individuals from being subject to these laws can cause severe problems.</p>
<p>Police violence against innocent students</p>
<p><object classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" width="450" height="370" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0" height="370" width="450" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0" classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000"><param name="wmode" value="transparent" /><param name="src" value="http://www.liveleak.com/e/99f_1205109799" /><embed type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="450" height="370" src="http://www.liveleak.com/e/99f_1205109799" height="370" width="450" src="http://www.liveleak.com/e/99f_1205109799" wmode="transparent" type="application/x-shockwave-flash"></embed></object></p>
<p>Violent Police tactics</p>
<p><object classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" width="425" height="344" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0" height="344" width="425" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0" classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000"><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><param name="src" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/tcUB5NQdrhg&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1" /><embed type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="425" height="344" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/tcUB5NQdrhg&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1" height="344" width="425" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/tcUB5NQdrhg&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" type="application/x-shockwave-flash"></embed></object></p>
<p>Apartheid mentality</p>
<p><img src="http://54beats.com/images/necklace.jpg" alt="" /></p>
<p>A situation which grants them potential absolute power, will naturally corrupt them absolutely. The easy freedom to use excessive force to solve a problem will naturally encourage the repetition of this sort of action. The idea that they are exempt and seemingly above the law, will encourage them to act in this way. Instead of serving and protecting they will merely  intimidate and bully. It seems as if history is repeating itself with potentially dire consequences.</p>
